This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it discusses a technical breakthrough in the domain of machine learning, specifically the use of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs). It also proposes a novel learning procedure for GANs to fit a distributed setup. 

It is also likely to belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as the paper uses the MNIST and CIFAR10 datasets, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as the paper addresses the problem of distributing GANs to train on datasets spread across multiple workers. 

It may also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as GANs are a type of AI model, and the paper proposes a new learning procedure for them. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as GANs are a type of neural network, and the paper discusses their performance in a distributed setting.
